Problems in the current implementation
=======================================

1. Loss of data-types  
   • Functions, `undefined`, `Infinity`, `-Infinity`, `NaN`, `Symbol`, `BigInt`, DOM nodes, class instances, getters / setters, non-enumerable properties, property descriptors, `Map`, `Set`, `RegExp`, `Date`, `ArrayBuffer`, TypedArrays, etc. are either dropped, converted to a different type, or will make `JSON.stringify` throw.  
   • `Date` becomes an ISO string; on re-parse it is no longer a `Date` object.  
   • `BigInt` or circular references throw `TypeError`.

2. Prototype is lost  
   The returned value is always a plain object (`Object.prototype`); any custom prototype chain, methods, or class identity (`instanceof`) are gone.

3. Circular references crash  
   `JSON.stringify` raises `TypeError: Converting circular structure to JSON`.

4. Security / side-effects  
   • `JSON.stringify` calls an object’s custom `toJSON()` method.  If the object is supplied by an attacker this method can run arbitrary code, potentially mutating application state, leaking data, or causing a DoS.  
   • Large attacker-controlled objects can blow up memory/CPU during stringify/parse (DoS).

5. Performance  
   For large objects this creates two full copies of the data as strings, stresses the GC, and is slow compared with native or iterative cloning.

6. Property attributes disappear  
   Enumerable only, writable/enumerable/configurable flags, getters/setters, frozen/sealed state, and `WeakMap` / `WeakSet` membership are not preserved.

How to fix / improve
====================

Preferred (modern runtimes)
---------------------------

```javascript
// Node ≥17.0 or modern browsers
function deepClone(obj) {
  return structuredClone(obj);   // handles Date, RegExp, Map, Set, ArrayBuffer,
                                 // TypedArrays, circular refs, etc.
}
```

Fallback for older environments
-------------------------------

```javascript
function deepClone(obj, seen = new WeakMap()) {
  if (obj === null || typeof obj !== 'object') return obj;          // primitives
  if (seen.has(obj)) return seen.get(obj);                          // circular

  let clone;

  // Handle built-ins explicitly
  if (obj instanceof Date) clone = new Date(obj);
  else if (obj instanceof RegExp) clone = new RegExp(obj);
  else if (obj instanceof Map) {
    clone = new Map();
    seen.set(obj, clone);
    obj.forEach((v, k) => clone.set(deepClone(k, seen), deepClone(v, seen)));
  } else if (obj instanceof Set) {
    clone = new Set();
    seen.set(obj, clone);
    obj.forEach(v => clone.add(deepClone(v, seen)));
  } else if (ArrayBuffer.isView(obj)) {
    clone = new obj.constructor(obj);
  } else if (Array.isArray(obj)) {
    clone = [];
    seen.set(obj, clone);
    obj.forEach((v, i) => (clone[i] = deepClone(v, seen)));
  } else {
    clone = Object.create(Object.getPrototypeOf(obj));
    seen.set(obj, clone);
    Reflect.ownKeys(obj).forEach(key => {
      const desc = Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(obj, key);
      if ('value' in desc) desc.value = deepClone(desc.value, seen);
      Object.defineProperty(clone, key, desc);
    });
  }

  return clone;
}
```

Other practical choices
-----------------------

• Use a battle-tested library such as `lodash.cloneDeep` or `rfdc`.  
• In Node.js <17 you can use `v8.serialize / v8.deserialize` (`require('v8')`) which preserves more types than JSON and supports circular structures.

Additional hardening
--------------------

1. If you must stick with `JSON.stringify` introduce a size cap:  
   ```
   const MAX_JSON_SIZE = 1e6; // 1 MB
   const json = JSON.stringify(obj);
   if (json.length > MAX_JSON_SIZE) throw new Error('Input too large');
   return JSON.parse(json);
   ```
2. Sanitize/validate untrusted objects before cloning to avoid running hostile `toJSON()`.  
3. Avoid cloning objects with privileged references (e.g., database connections, file handles) – cloning merely copies references and may break invariants.

Summary
=======

`return JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))` is a neat one-liner but is only safe for small, acyclic, data-only objects made of primitives, plain arrays, and simple POJOs. For anything beyond that, switch to `structuredClone`, a dedicated deep-cloning routine, or a reputable library, and always consider the size and trust level of the data you are cloning.
